Code value="ncat"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Content Types</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gterr"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfact"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">Factiva Filters</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gterr"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code><Code value="nfcpex"><CodeD index="no" lang="en">C&amp;E Executive News Filter</CodeD><CodeI org="expansion" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="root" value="ns:gterr"/></CodeI><CodeI org="validation" action="add"><CodeA name="db" value="pedv---00000997-20180320-161217"/><CodeA name="status" value="active"/></CodeI></Code></CSet></CodeSets><DescTPC fid="de"><DescField fid="ipc">N/CRM N/DJN N/GEN N/TER N/WER R/AFG R/ASI R/NME R/US </DescField><DescField fid="ipd">NWREGULAR WSJ WSJ.com WSJ.com Site Search WSJAsia WSJEurope WSJ Japanese Online WSJ-PRO-WSJ.com WSJSunday AFGHAN SECTARIAN VIOLENCE AFGHAN WAR AGHANISTAN SUICIDE BOMBING ISLAMIC STATE KABUL BOMBING KARTE SAKHI MOSQUE NOWRUZ PERSIAN NEW YEAR SUICIDE ATTTACK SUICIDE BOMBING SB126955385469309739639045841150622740657061 Donald Trump Ghani, Ashraf PRO SYND WSJ-PRO-NP CODES_REVIEWED Wires Asia News </DescField><DescField fid="ipcns">OASN OWON </DescField></DescTPC></MetadataPT><ArchiveDoc xml:space="preserve"><Article markup="pp0" lang="en" index="field"><HandL fid="hlp"><Title fid="hl"><SectionName fid="se" index="field">World</SectionName><ColumnName fid="clm" index="field"></ColumnName><Headline fid="hd"><Para lang="en">Suicide Bomber, in Crowd of New Year Pilgrims, Kills Dozens in Kabul; Islamic State claimed responsibility for the attack in Afghanistan</Para></Headline></Title><LeadPara fid="lp"><Para>KABUL—A suspected Islamic State suicide bomber disguised as a street musician triggered explosives hidden inside of a drum, killing at least 34 people among throngs of revelers gathered in the Afghan capital Kabul to celebrate the Persian New Year, a senior Afghan security official said.</Para><Para>Islamic State, through its Amaq news agency, claimed responsibility for the attack, which occurred on the first day of a two-day national holiday marking the Persian New Year and despite hundreds of additional police and soldiers deployed across the capital to protect Afghans enjoying their day off.</Para></LeadPara></HandL><TailParas fid="td"><Para>The assertion of responsibility by Islamic State couldn't be independently confirmed, but the radical Sunni Muslim group's local affiliate has frequently targeted Shiite Muslims in Kabul in the past year, apparently seeking to deepen the country's sectarian divisions and destabilize the U.S.-backed government of Ashraf Ghani. The Taliban denied any involvement in the bombing.</Para><Para>The attack highlighted the threat of terrorist violence that has escalated in the Afghan capital in the past year, bedeviling even the most heavily guarded areas of the city. Hundreds of people have been killed in high-profile attacks, which have rattled even city residents familiar with violence and fueled public dissatisfaction with the government of President Ghani.</Para><Para>Army Gen. John W. Nicholson Jr., the commander of U.S. and NATO forces here, told reporters last week that defending Kabul is now the main aim of the U.S.-led coalition in Afghanistan.</Para><Para>In response to the increasing deadliness of attacks in the capital, the U.S. is stepping up Special Operations missions in the city, as well as efforts to identify and locate terrorist networks in the city, he said.</Para><Para>Wednesday's attack, which also wounded 22 people, took place in the western neighborhood of Karte Sakhi, near both Kabul University and a Shiite shrine especially popular during the Persian New Year, known as Nowruz. The bomber was playing the drum to draw passersby when he set off his disguised bomb, the security official said.</Para><Para>Islamic State, the Taliban and other Muslim fundamentalist movements view as un-Islamic Nowruz and any religion, religious observance or seasonal celebration that predates the founding of Islam in the 7th century. Nowruz has its roots in Zoroastrianism, and versions of it have been observed across the Middle East and Central Asia for more than 3,000 years.</Para><Para>The size of Islamic State's affiliate in Afghanistan—Islamic State-Khorasan Province—and the danger it poses are hotly disputed. Among United Nations and Afghan security officials, as well as country experts, estimates of its ranks range from 500-5,000 fighters.</Para><Para>Yet any attempt at gauging its actual strength is complicated by the allegiances of armed radical Islamists, which shift, often by the month or week, depending on ideological shifts, financing and the tide of battle.</Para><Para>Although any estimate of the size of Islamic State is dwarfed by the numbers that make up the Taliban, the country's largest insurgency, the issue also has become a geopolitical football, with Russia, in particular, pressing the Afghan government to take action against what it says are thousands of the group's fighters in the north of the country, along what Moscow considers its southern tier.</Para><Para>In testimony to the House Armed Services Committee last month, Army Gen. Joseph Votel, head of U.S. Central Command, said Russia had "exaggerated" the threat posed by an Islamic State affiliate in Afghanistan and had mischaracterized that group's rise as an indication of a failed U.S. strategy.</Para><Para>Before President Donald Trump in August announced a new, invigorated U.S. policy in Afghanistan, much of the U.S. military's attention was focused in the east of the country on containing Islamic State, whose goal of international jihad is considered more dangerous than the Taliban's largely nationalist goals.</Para><Para>Last April, a KC-130 cargo plane last April <ELink type="webpage" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-drops-its-largest-non-nuclear-bomb-on-isis-tunnel-complex-in-afghanistan-1492104067">dropped a 22,000-pound GBU-43/B Massive Ordnance Air Blast</ELink>—known colloquially as the Mother of All Bombs—on a tunnel complex in eastern Nangarhar province used by Islamic State-Khorasan Province. It was the first use in combat of the most powerful nonnuclear bomb in America's arsenal, the Pentagon said.</Para><Para>Navy Capt. Thomas Gresback, spokesman for the U.S.-led coalition in Afghanistan, said in January 1,600 Islamic State militants had been killed in Afghanistan in 2017 and that the threat the group poses wasn't growing. It was active in only three of the country's 34 provinces, he said.</Para><Para>Ehsanullah Amiri and Habib Khan Totakhil contributed to this article.</Para><Para>Write to Craig Nelson at <ELink type="webpage" ref="mailto:craig.nelson@wsj.com">craig.nelson@wsj.com</ELink></Para></TailParas><Byline fid="by" index="field">By Craig Nelson </Byline><Credit fid="cr" index="field"></Credit><Contact fid="ct" index="field"></Contact><Notes fid="rf" index="field"></Notes><Art fid="art" index="field"></Art><Copyright fid="cy" index="field">Copyright 2018 Dow Jones &amp; Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved. </Copyright></Article></ArchiveDoc><AdocTOC adoctype="article"><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/ArchiveDoc::Article" type="arttext"></Item><Item size="0" ref="distdoc:archive/InvertText" type="invtext"></Item><Item subtype="primary" size="0" ref="https://www.wsj.com/articles/suicide-bomber-in-crowd-of-new-year-pilgrims-kills-dozens-1521630534" type="webpage"></Item></AdocTOC></DistDoc>

